Obfuscation

Learn how to secure your app through obscurity.

We'll cover the following
    • Obscurity
    • Obfuscation beyond security

Obscurity#

Have you heard the phrase: security through obscurity? It’s rarely true, but in some cases, helpful. Most applications use an ID field in each table as a primary key. This ID is then used throughout the system to access data. It is passed through URLs, forms, and APIs to denote the needed piece of data.

Sometimes, you don’t want to expose the user to the actual row ID. Maybe you are launching a new product and don’t want the user to know that they are only the 13th user. Perhaps you have public data but don’t want your site to be easily crawled by scraping bots.

In these cases, you can obfuscate the ID to something that isn’t incremental but can be translated to your ID field. Rather than doing this: You could do:

app.all(
  '/blog/:blogId/edit',
  isAuthenticated,
  isEditor,
  function(req, res) {
      //id = 4321234
      var post = db.post().where({
        'id': req.params.blogId
      }).row();
});

You could do:

var Hashids = require('hashids');
var hashids = new Hashids('App-wide salt');
app.all(
    '/blog/:blogHash/edit',
    isAuthenticated,
    isEditor,
    function(req, res) {
        var id = hashids.decode(req.params.blogHash);
        var post = db.post().where({
            'id': id
        }).row();
    }
);
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

In this example, the hashids.decode() call is simply taking some preexisting security hash from your server and applying it against the passed hash to determine the ID. This can also be called in reverse to generate a hash. Here’s a demo of both operations:

/
app.js
  • app.js

var Hashids = require('hashids');
var hashids = new Hashids('App-wide salt');
var hash = hashids.encode(4321234);
console.log("Encoded:", hash);
var decode = hashids.decode(hash);
console.log("Decoded:", decode);
Enter to Rename, Shift+Enter to Preview

It is trivial to write these hashing methods yourself, but I recommend using the tried and true HashIDs libraries. These libraries are easy-to-use, well-maintained, and available across many different programming languages to ensure interoperability throughout your entire infrastructure.

Obfuscation beyond security#

There are cases where obfuscation is needed or even required. For example, obscurity can be an additional safeguard for HIPAA’s data. One use case was a specification that required keeping HIPAA sensitive data in a separate database. In this case, it was a three-tier server architecture. Primary keys used by the web application were stored in one database, along with non-sensitive data. Sensitive data was stored in another. An intermediary database stored the relations. This was designed so if one database was compromised, the data obtained would be anonymous or non-sensitive.

It bears repeating: in most cases, obscurity doesn’t protect from any legitimate attacks. Don’t rely on it for security. It is a means of making things a little harder to find.
